## Frontend Validation (Admin + App)

Use Zod for all form validation.

```ts
// validations/user.validation.ts
import { z } from 'zod';

export const createUserSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email('Invalid email address'),
  password: z
    .string()
    .min(8, 'Password must be at least 8 characters')
    .regex(/[A-Z]/, 'Must contain uppercase')
    .regex(/[0-9]/, 'Must contain a number'),
  name: z.string().min(2).max(100),
  role: z.nativeEnum(UserRole),
  phone: z.string().optional(),
});

export type CreateUserInput = z.infer<typeof createUserSchema>;
```

Connect to React Hook Form:

```ts
const form = useForm<CreateUserInput>({
  resolver: zodResolver(createUserSchema),
});
```

---

## Validation Rules

- All backend DTOs use class-validator — no exceptions
- All frontend forms use Zod schema — no `useState`-based manual validation
- Error messages must be user-friendly (not internal codes)
- Schemas live in their own file — never inline in components or controllers
- Reuse shared schemas across create/update via `PartialType`/`z.partial()`
- Always validate on both frontend (UX) and backend (security) — never trust frontend alone

---

## Forbidden

❌ Validating only on frontend — backend must also validate
❌ `any` type in DTOs or Zod schemas
❌ Validation logic inside service methods that belongs in DTOs
❌ Zod schemas inside JSX/TSX component files
❌ Plain `interfaces` for request validation (use DTOs with decorators)
❌ Generic error messages like "Invalid input" — be specific
❌ Skipping `forbidNonWhitelisted` — always strip unexpected fields
